1.description:
Welcome to Strategic Game of Life! This is the first tutorial level. The entire Game of Life is governed by the following four rules:
  1. Any live cell with fewer than two live neighbours dies.
  2. Any live cell with two or three live neighbours lives.
  3. Any live cell with more than three live neighbours dies.
  4. Any dead cell with exactly three live neighbours becomes a live cell.
If you're interested in learning more, read about the Game of Life on WikiPedia.

Do you see that shape in the middle of the screen? It's called a Glider. And that rainbow tile is the Goal. Click play and watch what happens. Note that this level isn't interactive.
1.name: Tutorial #1: Hello Glider

10.description:
This is another non-interactive level.

Notice how simple the Multum in Parvo pattern in the middle of the arena is, and yet how unpredictabley complex it can become.
10.name: Chaos #2: Multum in Parvo

11.description:
Alright, it's time for your first real mission! Try to tear your way through the barrier and get to the Goal!

If your first attempt fails, remember that you can move something you build by a single tile, and the outcome can be completely different.
11.name: Fanblades I

12.description:
Notice the red zones. These are Dead Zones. No cells will become alive in these zones, so you'll have to find a way to get around them.

As a hint, see what happens when that Spaceship crashes into a wall...

Also, remember that everything in the library can be rotated and flipped, and if you move something by a single tile, the outcome can be completely different.
12.name: Hookshot

13.description: This level can be beaten using the same method you beat the last level.
13.name: Flock of Gliders

14.description:
Lots of stuff going on here. Those two big connected shapes are called Pentadecathlon, and they go through a chain reaction before stabilizing into an animation.

There are also some Blinkers and Still Lifes thrown into the mix for fun, as well as an annoying Dead Zone getting in your way.

Remember that you can often just throw a Glider into the chaos and things work themselves out.
14.name: Pentadecathlon

15.description:
Remember that Glider Gun you saw a while ago? Well, it's back! Unfortunately, there's an Eater preventing any gliders from hitting the Goal.

An Eater, when placed just right, will destroy a Glider and retain its shape.

For them to work, a Glider needs to hit it at just the right angle. If the Eater oscillates, it needs to hit at the right frame of animation as well. Otherwise, if these strict conditions aren't met, it will be damaged or destroyed entirely.
15.name: Abaddon: Destroyer of Worlds

16.description:
Whoa! Look at that giant slow-moving ship moving towards the Goal! We call this thing Sparky.

Unfortunately, it won't set off the Goal, and will even serve to get in your way.

Try to activate the Goal even though that big thing is in your way!
16.name: Hey there Sparky!

17.description:
The six Blinkers on the left can have their construction finished by playing a tile in the center of them, which will cause a horizontal Spaceship to collide.

You don't want to cause every ship to collide with a Blinker though; some you just want to hit the far left wall.

Find some combination of enabled Blinkers to set off the goal.
17.name: Gated Spaceship Depot

18.description:
This simple construct is called Gliders by the Dozen. If you watch the pretty symmetical animation it plays, you'll soon find out where it gets its name from.

Good luck activating the Goal amidst all of the chaos!
18.name: God Complex

19.description:
Sure, you just beat this level a moment ago, and if I had to guess, you probably sent some Gliders towards it at a 45° angle.

Can you beat the same level with these new Dead Zones in your way?
19.name: Complex God

2.description:
Now that you kinda have a feel for how the game works, and you've seen a simulation in action, try to recreate that same Glider pattern you saw in the previous level. For your convenience, its pattern has been added to your library.

Every pattern you discover in the Game of Life can always be rotated 90° or even flipped horizontally or vertically and will still work the same (although, if the patterns move, they will move in a different direction).

You can only alter the state of cells within the green Playable Zone.
2.name: Tutorial #2: Build a Glider

20.description:
This mission is a lot like a previous one, except that the playable area has changed quite a bit.

Remember that unpredictable things can happen when two objects collide.
20.name: Fanblades II

21.description:
This crazy three pronged spaceship is called an Orion 2, and is moving towards the upper left corner of the arena, which is where your playable zone is!

Can you get past the ship and activate the Goal?
21.name: Orion's Belt

22.description:
Here is another level with a simple pattern in the middle, which goes through a bunch of chaos before stabilizing into some Oscillators and Still Lifes.

And, would you look at that? There's a Dead Zone right outside of the playable area!

Try to activate the Goal even with these hassles in the way!
22.name: Many Hats

23.description: The backdrop of this level consists of a field of Blinkers, and the Goal is surrounded by several Dead Zones.
23.name: <blink><blink>blink</blink></blink>

24.description:
This one looks pretty difficult. You can't simply send a Spaceship up and crash it into the wall and spawn a Glider, as the horizontal gap is too small.

As a hint, I was able to beat this on Generation 432 with 20 Cells in Play.
24.name: Getting Difficult

25.description:
Other than a few Still Lifes protecting the Goal, this isn't too interesting of a level. Unless, you consider, that there is no line of sight between you and the Goal, and you may need to play off of two separate walls to reach the Goal.

This level was first beaten by @endeavourize with 18 Cells Played and 375 Generations.
25.name: Round the Bend

3.description:
This time, there's something in the way of your Goal! This simple shape is called a Blinker, and will flip between being horizontal and vertical. Since there are two \"frames\" of this animation, it can be thought of as a Period 2 Oscillator.

If you draw a Glider in the lower right corner of the playfield, then draw another one to the upper left of it, the first should destroy the barrier, and the second can activate the Goal.
3.name: Tutorial #3: Build more Gliders

4.description:
Anything you do in the Game of Life can always be flipped or roated and the effect will likewise be flipped or roated.

Notice how the Glider you saw in the last level behaves differently depending on the direction it is pointed.
4.name: Tutorial #4: Symmetry

6.description:
In this level we have two Spaceships. Much like a Glider, a Spaceship can move across the playing field and retain its original shape.

An interesting phenomenon happens when a spaceship collides with the edge of the field. Depending on it's distance from the edge, it will form a glider which will travel either right or left from the wall, depending on the distance.

If you ever find yourself wanting to get around a corner be sure to try this technique, adjusting the distance if necessary.
6.name: Tutorial #6: Intro to Spaceship

7.description:
Using your newfound knowledge of Spaceships, try to activate the goal in this level.

Notice the red rectangle. This is called a deadzone, no cells will survive inside of it. These will have the same effect as the edge of a map when something collides with it.
7.name: Tutorial #7: Build a Spaceship

8.description: Notice what happens when we change the distance of the spaceship from a wall by a single cell!
8.name: Tutorial #8: Chaos

9.description:
This is another non-interactive level. Just click play and watch what happens!

The Game of Life can allow for some complex interactions, and as you're about to see, the results can be quite interesting.

The object in the upper left corner of the arena is called a Gosper Glider Gun and as you can tell it is aptly named.
9.name: Chaos #1: What is a Glider Gun

dictionary.how_to_play:
How to Play

Tap the arena in a green Playable Zone to toggle cells.

No cells can be alive in the red Dead Zones.

The rainbow tiles are Goal tiles and need to be activiated to beat levels.

Conway's Game of Life

The Game of Life is governed by the following four rules:

  1. Any live cell with fewer than two live neighbours dies.
  2. Any live cell with two or three live neighbours lives.
  3. Any live cell with more than three live neighbours dies.
  4. Any dead cell with exactly three live neighbours becomes a live cell.

If you're interested in learning more, read about Conway's Game of Life on WikiPedia.
